# Architectural Context — {{PROJECT_NAME}}

## Architectural Style

{{PROJECT_NAME}} follows **Hexagonal Architecture (Ports & Adapters)**. The application core is the hexagon at the center; everything that crosses the boundary does so through an explicitly named port.

## The Hexagon

The core contains:
- **Use cases** — the operations the application offers to the world
- **Domain model** — entities, value objects, business rules
- **Ports** — interfaces that describe what the core offers (inbound) and what it needs (outbound)

The core is pure: no HTTP, no SQL, no framework imports. It can be tested entirely with stubs/fakes for its outbound ports.

## Ports

### Inbound ports (driving side)
{{INBOUND_PORTS_DESCRIPTION}}

These are interfaces the core exposes. Driving adapters call them. Examples:
- `BookRoomUseCase` — invoked by an HTTP handler
- `ProcessPaymentCommand` — invoked by a message consumer

### Outbound ports (driven side)
{{OUTBOUND_PORTS_DESCRIPTION}}

These are interfaces the core depends on. Driven adapters implement them. Examples:
- `BookingRepository` — implemented by a Postgres adapter
- `NotificationGateway` — implemented by an SMTP or SNS adapter

## Adapters

### Driving adapters
{{DRIVING_ADAPTERS_DESCRIPTION}}

Translate external triggers into inbound port calls. Examples: HTTP controllers, gRPC servers, CLI commands, message consumers, scheduled jobs.

### Driven adapters
{{DRIVEN_ADAPTERS_DESCRIPTION}}

Translate outbound port calls into operations against external systems. Examples: SQL repositories, REST clients, message publishers.

## Composition Root

The composition root (typically in `cmd/` or `main.go`) is the **only** place that knows about both ports and concrete adapters. It wires them together at startup.

